11:35.929 --> 11:39.265 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what does it tell you about what
happened on that night in

11:39.299 --> 11:41.267 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
October a year ago? DAVID
KLINGER, Professor, University

11:41.301 --> 11:44.337 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of Missouri-Saint Louis: What I
see is, I see a tactical failure

11:44.370 --> 11:47.273 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the part of the officer that
ended up shooting, as well as

11:47.307 --> 11:50.343 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
his partner. And what I mean by
that is, police officers, when

11:50.376 --> 11:54.013 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they're dealing with individuals
who are reportedly armed with an

11:54.047 --> 11:57.083 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
edged weapon, a knife, a
hatchet, a machete, what they're

11:57.116 --> 12:00.186 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
trained to do is, they are
trained to try to keep distance.

12:00.219 --> 12:04.324 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so if you look at the video,
what we see from the back of Mr.

12:04.357 --> 12:07.293 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
McDonald as he's walking toward
these police officers is, he

12:07.327 --> 12:10.863 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
moves away and the officers
actually move towards him away

12:10.897 --> 12:13.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
from their vehicle. And so
that's the very first thing that

12:13.900 --> 12:17.403 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I saw. And I'm thinking, this
really doesn't make any sense. I

12:17.437 --> 12:20.173 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was thinking at first perhaps
there was maybe some innocent

12:20.206 --> 12:22.809 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
people on the opposite side of
the street. I checked the video

12:22.842 --> 12:25.078 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a couple, three times. There is
no evidence that there were any

12:25.111 --> 12:28.548 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
other citizens who might be in
jeopardy, and so it didn't make

12:28.581 --> 12:32.585 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
any sense. And then, when the
gunshots start to ring out, I

12:32.619 --> 12:36.489 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
couldn't understand why shots
were being fired. Then McDonald

12:36.522 --> 12:39.292 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
falls down, and I don't
understand why additional shots

12:39.325 --> 12:44.364 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are fired. And so, as I look at
this, I am scratching my head,

12:44.397 --> 12:47.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
figuratively, because it doesn't
add up. It doesn't appear to me

12:47.767 --> 12:50.269 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to be what we call a reasonable
use of deadly force. JUDY

12:50.303 --> 12:54.674 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: So, the lawyer for the
officer is saying -- we just

12:54.707 --> 12:59.412 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
heard him say that, from a
different perspective, this

12:59.445 --> 13:02.248 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
officer saw something that we
are not able to see in this

13:02.281 --> 13:06.219 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
video. What could that possibly
be? DAVID KLINGER: I don't know.

13:06.252 --> 13:10.256 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, at one point, I do agree
with the lawyer that a video is

13:10.289 --> 13:13.860 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
never dispositive, because it
doesn't tell everything. What

13:13.893 --> 13:17.664 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the courts have ruled for a long
time, for over 30 years now --

13:17.697 --> 13:20.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or excuse me -- for 30 years
now, is you have to take the

13:20.066 --> 13:23.569 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
totality of the circumstances
into account when you're looking

13:23.603 --> 13:27.240 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at what police officers do. And
then in 1989 in Graham v.

13:27.273 --> 13:30.510 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Connor, the U.S. Supreme Court
said that you can't look at it

13:30.543 --> 13:33.513 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with 20/20 hindsight, but rather
through the eyes of a reasonable

13:33.546 --> 13:37.383 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
police officer on or at the
scene. And so, consequently, we

13:37.417 --> 13:40.453 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
do have to take into account
everything in addition to the

13:40.486 --> 13:43.956 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
video that might be relevant.
What that might be that would

13:43.990 --> 13:47.293 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
overturn what appears to be a
clear-cut case of unreasonable

13:47.326 --> 13:49.962 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
force, I don't know what it is.
But, certainly, the

13:49.996 --> 13:52.932 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
investigation is never over
merely because a video comes

13:52.965 --> 13:55.635 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
forth. We have to hear the
officer's statement, partner's

13:55.668 --> 13:58.971 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
statement, listen to the
dispatch tapes. Maybe there's

13:59.005 --> 14:01.240 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
other video, maybe there's other
audio we're unaware of. The

14:01.274 --> 14:05.712 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bottom line is that the officer
has been charged with homicide,

14:05.745 --> 14:09.215 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with first-degree murder, and he
deserves his day in court, and

14:09.248 --> 14:11.350 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
he deserves to have the
opportunity to put forth a

14:11.384 --> 14:13.586 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
defense. And we will have to see
what the defense is. JUDY

14:13.619 --> 14:17.056 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: You started out
describing what an officer might

14:17.090 --> 14:20.593 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
do approaching someone, you
said, with an edged weapon. What

14:20.626 --> 14:24.931 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is the standard of practice for
an officer in a situation like

14:24.964 --> 14:27.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
this? I know you can't
generalize across every part of

14:27.300 --> 14:30.136 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the country, but in general,
what would be the practice an

14:30.169 --> 14:34.807 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
officer is advised to take?
DAVID KLINGER: In a situation

14:34.841 --> 14:36.809 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
where you're dealing with an
individual with a knife, a

14:36.843 --> 14:39.045 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hatchet, some other form of
edged weapon, you want to try to

14:39.078 --> 14:41.781 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
keep distance. And the reason
you want to try to keep distance

14:41.814 --> 14:45.118 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is if you are 30 or 40 or 50
feet away, it's awfully hard for

14:45.151 --> 14:48.588 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that individual armed with that
weapon to harm you with it. But

14:48.621 --> 14:51.991 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
when a suspect is within about
20 to 25 feet -- it depends on

14:52.024 --> 14:53.993 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
what training block of
instruction you might get in a

14:54.026 --> 14:56.596 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
given police department around
the country -- that's what we

14:56.629 --> 15:00.399 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
call the zone where an officer
could reasonably perceive that

15:00.433 --> 15:03.436 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
his or her life is in jeopardy
if someone is moving towards

15:03.469 --> 15:06.539 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
them. JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.
DAVID KLINGER: And the reason

15:06.572 --> 15:09.442 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for that is basically threefold.
Number one, it takes time to

15:09.475 --> 15:11.444 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
perceive something and react to
it. Were you trying to cut me

15:11.477 --> 15:13.446 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
off, ma'am? JUDY WOODRUFF: No, I
was -- because I just wanted to

15:13.479 --> 15:15.448 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
get to one -- one question.
DAVID KLINGER: OK. JUDY

15:15.481 --> 15:17.617 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOODRUFF: And that is, when
someone is down on the ground,

15:17.650 --> 15:21.420 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what justifies continuing to
fire round after round at that

15:21.454 --> 15:25.925 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
person? DAVID KLINGER: In this
situation, I can't see anything

15:25.958 --> 15:28.861 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that would justify it. However,
if an individual was armed with

15:28.895 --> 15:31.564 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a firearm, it really doesn't
matter if they're standing up,

15:31.597 --> 15:34.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sitting down or laying down. If
they are moving that firearm in

15:34.767 --> 15:37.570 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a fashion that could threaten
someone, i.e., they could be

15:37.603 --> 15:41.741 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
continuing to pull the trigger,
then that would be justifiable.

15:41.774 --> 15:44.644 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, in this situation, as far
as I know -- and I haven't heard

15:44.677 --> 15:48.147 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
any claim that there was any
indication at all that the

15:48.181 --> 15:51.217 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
suspect was armed with a firearm
-- it wouldn't make any sense to

15:51.250 --> 15:53.953 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
continue to fire. JUDY WOODRUFF:
Professor David Klinger,

15:53.986 --> 15:56.756 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
University of Missouri-Saint
Louis, we thank you. DAVID

15:56.789 --> 15:59.826 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KLINGER: Thank you for having
me. JUDY WOODRUFF: And, next, we

15:59.859 --> 16:02.695 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hear from two reporters who have
been closely following these

16:02.728 --> 16:05.965 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
events. They both have years of
experience covering Chicago

16:05.998 --> 16:09.969 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
crime, policing, and race
relations. Mark Konkol is a

16:10.002 --> 16:14.907 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
columnist at DNA Info. It's a
neighborhood reporting site. In

16:14.941 --> 16:19.745 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
2011, he and a team at The
Chicago Sun-Times won a Pulitzer

16:19.779 --> 16:23.015 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Prize for their reporting on
violence, crime and policing in

16:23.049 --> 16:27.086 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Chicago. And Jamie Kalven is a
freelance journalist. He

16:27.119 --> 16:31.123 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
uncovered the autopsy report
showing that Laquan McDonald was

16:31.157 --> 16:35.761 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
shot 16 times by officer Jason
Van Dyke. Kalven is also the

16:35.795 --> 16:39.232 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
founder of the Invisible
Institute. It's a nonprofit

16:39.265 --> 16:42.969 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
journalism project that recently
released tens of thousands of

16:43.002 --> 16:47.740 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pages of civilian complaints
filed against the Chicago Police

16:47.773 --> 16:50.576 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Department. And, gentlemen, we
thank you both for being with

16:50.610 --> 16:54.680 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
us. Mark Konkol, let me start
with you. How does this incident

16:54.714 --> 16:59.518 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fit into the bigger picture of
Chicago police relations with

16:59.552 --> 17:02.855 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the African-American community
in that city? MARK KONKOL,

17:02.889 --> 17:06.359 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DNAinfo: Well, I think that it's
just a big example of what's

17:06.392 --> 17:09.762 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
been happening for a long time.
There is a severe lack of trust

17:09.795 --> 17:13.799 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
between people who live in
poverty-stricken communities

17:13.833 --> 17:18.271 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that are crippled by violence
and fractured gang wars. And

17:18.304 --> 17:20.640 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Chicago -- the Chicago Police
Department, there's a lot of

17:20.673 --> 17:24.010 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
good cops on the department. I
would say the overwhelming

17:24.043 --> 17:28.814 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
majority, 90 percent, 95 percent
-- and there's been stories

17:28.848 --> 17:33.386 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
written that, you know, there is
a few officers that are

17:33.419 --> 17:37.957 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
troubled. But, overall, the
police department has a

17:37.990 --> 17:43.062 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
generational problem that a
federal judge said was a culture

17:43.095 --> 17:47.199 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that's of the public interest,
and that is the thin blue line

17:47.233 --> 17:50.636 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
code of silence within the
department. And it's something

17:50.670 --> 17:55.241 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that's really wrong with the
department. And Cook County

17:55.274 --> 17:59.078 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
President Toni Preckwinkle
recently said that the culture

17:59.111 --> 18:05.084 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of law enforcement isn't
trusted, and it's just -- this

18:05.117 --> 18:09.522 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
incident highlights that to the
nth degree. And the protests

18:09.555 --> 18:13.092 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
really aren't just about one
incident. It's about being fed

18:13.125 --> 18:15.861 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
up. JUDY WOODRUFF: Right. MARK
KONKOL: And I think that's the

18:15.895 --> 18:18.197 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
message that these protesters
have been sending and that

18:18.230 --> 18:20.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
public officials have been
sending as well. JUDY WOODRUFF:

18:20.733 --> 18:23.469 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Let me turn to you, Jamie
Kalven. As we said, you were

18:23.502 --> 18:29.408 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
part of the effort to uncover
the documents that showed just

18:29.442 --> 18:34.413 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what happened on that night and
a broader practice among Chicago

18:34.447 --> 18:40.853 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
police. It's been 13 months
since Laquan McDonald was killed

18:40.886 --> 18:45.725 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- died. What could explain the
delay in releasing this video

18:45.758 --> 18:49.462 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and in charging this officer, as
he was yesterday? JAMIE KALVEN,

18:49.495 --> 18:52.064 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Invisible Institute: I think
that's the essential question at

18:52.098 --> 18:57.036 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this point. Everything that we
now know the day after the video

18:57.069 --> 19:01.407 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was released was known by the
city, by the department within

19:01.440 --> 19:07.346 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hours of Laquan McDonald's
death. There were multiple

19:07.380 --> 19:11.250 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
witnesses, police witnesses,
civilian witnesses. There was

19:11.283 --> 19:15.454 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the video, and the autopsy you
referred to before was actually

19:15.488 --> 19:20.159 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
conducted at 8:30 the next
morning with an investigator

19:20.192 --> 19:23.629 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
from the Independent Police
Review Authority, the city

19:23.662 --> 19:28.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
agency tasked with investigating
police shootings in the room.

19:28.034 --> 19:31.504 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, you know, with all of that
information, the information

19:31.537 --> 19:36.876 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that has been the basis now for
the indictment of officer Van

19:36.909 --> 19:40.079 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Dyke, the city put out, the
police department put out a

19:40.112 --> 19:46.452 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
press release saying that the
young man had approached and

19:46.485 --> 19:51.690 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
lunged toward the police
officers and was shot as an act

19:51.724 --> 19:55.694 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of self-defense on the part of
officer Van Dyke. They have to

19:55.728 --> 19:59.198 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have known that that was a
fabrication. Now, 13 months

19:59.231 --> 20:03.436 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
later, we're getting a quite
different narrative. So, I mean,

20:03.469 --> 20:08.207 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this -- if this had been a gang
shooting in Chicago, with this

20:08.240 --> 20:14.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
amount of evidence, witnesses,
video, the information from the

20:14.313 --> 20:19.085 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
autopsy, I imagine it would have
been weeks, you know, a matter

20:19.118 --> 20:22.621 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of a few weeks before an
indictment was returned. So I

20:22.655 --> 20:25.124 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
think -- I don't know the answer
to that question, but I think it

20:25.157 --> 20:28.527 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is the question of the moment.
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark Konkol, what

20:28.561 --> 20:32.164 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- what do you know about your
reporting on the Chicago police

20:32.198 --> 20:36.001 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that could explain this, the
delay? MARK KONKOL: Well, one of

20:36.035 --> 20:39.839 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the -- there is a provision in
the Chicago Police Department's

20:39.872 --> 20:43.976 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
union contract that says when
there is a complaint of

20:44.009 --> 20:49.348 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
misconduct against an officer,
the city, the citizen review

20:49.381 --> 20:54.420 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
board is not allowed to release
the name or any -- identify the

20:54.453 --> 20:58.090 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
officer in any way unless the
complaint is sustained. When we

20:58.124 --> 21:02.228 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bring up the fact that officer
Van Dyke had 18 misconduct

21:02.261 --> 21:07.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
complaints, all of them which
were not sustained, some people

21:09.802 --> 21:12.304 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
think that's a red flag, and
that that's something that the

21:12.338 --> 21:15.341 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
public should know when it
actually happens. When there is

21:15.374 --> 21:17.343 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a police shooting, reporters
across the city file Freedom of

21:17.376 --> 21:19.345 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Information Act requests to get
the video of the shooting, and

21:19.378 --> 21:21.347 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they're always doing that for
the same reason, that the case

21:21.380 --> 21:23.349 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is under investigation. It's a
very broad statement that police

21:23.382 --> 21:25.351 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
use. (CROSSTALK) JUDY WOODRUFF:
And we heard the prosecutor...

21:25.384 --> 21:27.353 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
(CROSSTALK) MARK KONKOL: ...
