34:21.059 --> 34:23.962 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
conversation is the speed of
light, right? We use the term

34:23.995 --> 34:28.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
speed of light in a haphazard
way all the time, but he meant

34:28.366 --> 34:31.503 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it in a very literal way. WALTER
ISAACSON: It begins with

34:31.536 --> 34:34.873 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Einstein trying to figure out,
why is the speed of light always

34:34.906 --> 34:37.275 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
constant, no matter which way
you're moving, if you're moving

34:37.309 --> 34:40.779 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
toward the source of the light
or away from it? And in 1905,

34:40.812 --> 34:44.449 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
when he was just a patent clerk
in the Swiss patent office, all

34:44.482 --> 34:47.285 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the physicists of Europe are
trying to figure this out. And

34:47.319 --> 34:51.222 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he begins his path to whole
theory of relativity by

34:51.256 --> 34:54.225 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
realizing that if you're
traveling really fast, say, to

34:54.259 --> 34:57.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
clock, it will look different
for you, whether it's

34:57.329 --> 35:00.098 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
synchronized, as somebody
traveling really fast in the

35:00.131 --> 35:03.902 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
other direction. And he comes up
with the amazing, sort of

35:03.935 --> 35:07.672 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
imaginatively, that, oh, I get
it, the speed of light is always

35:07.706 --> 35:11.209 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
constant, but time is relevant
depending on your state of

35:11.242 --> 35:14.579 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
motion. So that's the first
building block of the whole

35:14.612 --> 35:17.415 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
theory of relativity. It's
called the special theory of

35:17.449 --> 35:20.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
relativity, because it was just
about constant velocity, motion

35:20.885 --> 35:23.121 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and the speed of light. GWEN
IFILL: And then gravity comes

35:23.154 --> 35:25.156 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
into the equation. WALTER
ISAACSON: Right. It takes him 10

35:25.190 --> 35:28.560 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
years to generalize this -- the
theory, because he's wondering,

35:28.593 --> 35:32.430 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what about the acceleration? And
his theory says, nothing can

35:32.464 --> 35:35.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
travel faster than the speed of
light. But Newton's theory of

35:35.467 --> 35:39.738 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
gravity said that gravity acts
instantaneously, the moon

35:39.771 --> 35:43.308 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pulling the sun, pulling the
Earth, vice versa. That's

35:43.341 --> 35:46.411 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
instantaneous. And Einstein is
trying to figure out how that

35:46.444 --> 35:50.448 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
could be, and so he realizes
that the effects you would feel

35:50.482 --> 35:54.552 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of acceleration, like if you're
in an car, an elevator car

35:54.586 --> 35:58.123 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
accelerating upwards, that feels
just like gravity. And he comes

35:58.156 --> 36:01.459 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
up with the equivalence theory,
that gravity and acceleration

36:01.493 --> 36:04.562 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are both really the same thing.
GWEN IFILL: Bowling ball and the

36:04.596 --> 36:07.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
trampoline, explain -- I love
that idea, that analogy.

36:07.799 --> 36:09.968 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
(CROSSTALK) WALTER ISAACSON:
That's another way he visualizes

36:10.001 --> 36:13.338 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it, because the cool thing about
Einstein is, he thinks visually

36:13.371 --> 36:15.907 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in imaginative thought
experiment. And one of them is

36:15.940 --> 36:19.411 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
rolling a big ball on a piece of
fabric. You and I can call it a

36:19.444 --> 36:23.048 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
trampoline. And what happens? It
curves the fabric. Now, if you

36:23.081 --> 36:26.418 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
roll some billiard balls behind
it, what happens? They roll and

36:26.451 --> 36:30.188 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
